[3] Germany (Bavaria)
Date: Fri 10 May 2013
Source: Kinderaerzrzte-im-netz [In Geman, machine translation, abbreviated & edited]
http://www.kinderaerzte-im-netz.de/bvkj/aktuelles1/show.php3?id=4535&nodeid=26


Measles outbreak in Bavaria -- doctors sound the alarm
-----------------------------------------------
According to the Bavarian State Office for Health and Food Safety (LGL) and the Health Office in Munich since early April [2013], nearly 60 people contracted measles. This mainly affects the government districts of Upper Bavaria and Swabia, including Augsburg, Donau-Ries, Oak Ried and Freising. More and more people, especially in the capital, have contracted this highly contagious virus infection. This week alone 16 new cases were reported in Munich -- and the number is increasing. Teenagers and young adults especially predominate among the victims. To prevent further spread of measles, Bavarian family doctors are now advising their patients to obtain vaccination against measles. The Bavarian House Medical Association (BHÃ„V) and the Professional Association of Child and Adolescent Physicians (BVKJ) are targeting those people who still have no protection against measles. For this it is essential that the large vaccination gaps that still exist particularly among adolescents and young adults should be closed quickly. These groups are therefore being specifically targetted by general practitioners and paediatricians. "This year there have been major measles clusters in Berlin -- now spreading again to affect Bavaria unfortunately. This is not acceptable. Two vaccinations against measles are required to provide adequate protection. Paediatricians and general practitioners jointly are striving to eliminate measles from Bavaria.

Although school entrance examinations show that vaccination coverage against measles in recent years has increased significantly, so far only the 5 and 6-year-old pupils from Mecklenburg-Vorpommern have reached the necessary vaccination level of over 95 percent for both vaccinations against measles. Consequently a backlog still exists with respect to children in preschool and school age. "We intend that almost 95 percent of all children in Bavaria will have had at least one dose of vaccine and almost 90 percent a 2nd vaccination against measles. We should be able, therefore, by 2015 to achieve the World Health Organization (WHO's) immunization target. That's why the GPs of children and adults are now working closely together as widely as possible to close the still existing vaccination gaps.

Each infected adult can spread infection to infants not yet vaccinated. And for these small children, measles can have serious long-term consequences warns Dr. Martin Long, chairman of the National Association of Bavarian Paediatric Physicians. Especially serious is chronic measles encephalitis, which can occur after illness in the 1st year of life. "The vaccination campaign against measles is part of a joint initiative by general practitioners and paediatricians in Bavaria to strengthen the primary care of patients in the Free State. Over 9000 practicing physicians function to provide comprehensive medical care in Bavaria. For this reason it will be necessary in the future to further invest in primary care," admonish both chairman.

