[4] Germany (Bavaria)
Date: Tue 14 May 2013
Source: Augsburger Allgemeiner [in German, trans. Sabine Zentis, edited]
http://www.augsburger-allgemeine.de/noerdlingen/Die-Masern-breiten-sich-weiter-aus-id24951411.html


Measles spread further
-------------------
Two more children in Deiningen are ill with measles. The sick children were in contact with the 1st cases of measles in Deiningen last week. Because of these cases and the persons who have been in contact precautionary measures are being taken to prevent the spread of the viral disease at the middle school Deiningen, the secondary school Wemding and at the Theodor-Heuss-Gymnasium.

"These are definitely measles" the medical officer Dr. Rainer Mainka said after examination of the children. Both children have not been vaccinated and because of another family member who is on a training course outside the district, the training centre is affected as well. According to Dr. Mainka one reason for the new cases is that the health department did not receive the complete information about contacts of the 1st cases of measles. "Now we constantly learn about other persons in contact which hadn't been notified to the authorities earlier."

The incubation period is 2 weeks. The health authorities now have to act accordingly; i.e., banning children from schools as with a 2 week incubation period the disease could spread on for quite some time and hoping this has not already happened. The cooperation with parents is crucial to protect public health Dr. Mainka made clear. The health department has now introduced various measures for the above 3 schools. In the 2 schools attended by the sick children vaccination documentation of all children has to be investigated as had been done last week in the day care centre in Deiningen. Dr. Mainka didn't disclose the details of the schools for privacy reasons of those affected.

Children not protected against measles by vaccination will be sent home and are banned from attending lessons. For all 3 schools the authorities issued a call to vaccinated the children against measles. "In Deiningen the sports club is affected thus virtually the whole population" Dr. Mainka states and calls upon all parents in the region of Deiningen, Wemding and Alerheim to have children not protected yet vaccinated immediately as the immunization rates are particularly low. Children not properly vaccinated should not attend family gatherings, social or sporting events.

Asked about warnings from members of the anti-vaccination movement Dr. Mainka said : "I have to respect their private opinions but my 1st priority is to protect public health and those affected by the disease from further damage"

